ollar industry and Black mothers have the lowest breastfeeding rates in the country. Since slavery, legal, political, and societal factors have routinely denied Black women the ability to choose how to feed their babies. In Skimmed, Andrea Freeman tells the riveting story of the Fultz quadruplets while uncovering how feeding America's youngest citizens is awash in social, legal, and cultural inequalities. This book highlights the making of a modern public health crisis, the four extraordinary girls whose stories encapsulate a nationwide injustice, and how we can fight for a healthier future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAfrican American infantsxNutritionzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aAfrican Americans in advertisingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aBreastfeedingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aHealth and racezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aInfant formulaszUnited StatesxMarketingxHistory. 0aQuadrupletszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aLAW / Health.2bisacsh  aFood oppression.  abreastfeeding.  afirst food.  afood justice.  aformula feeding.  ahealth disparities.  apublic health.  aracism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2020 Englishz978311070486008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2020z9783110704587oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311069228040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361081140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503610811423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503610811.jpg  a978-3-11-069228-0  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-070471